Post-processing pass over a fully-typed batch of dictionary entries: forces `terminal = false` on any entry whose `/`-joined stroke is a strict prefix of another entry's stroke in the same batch (e.g. `STKWR-PBGS` is never terminal if `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT` also exists). This corrects a blind spot in `expand_types_one` (elsewhere in `expand/`), which classifies terminality one entry at a time and can't see that a zero-`%t`-slot "family root" placeholder is always superseded by a longer chord sharing its prefix. Must run once, after every entry in the batch has been typed — it's a whole-batch correction, not a per-entry rule.

`proper_prefixes(stroke: &str) -> Vec<String>` returns every proper leading `/`-segment prefix of a stroke (`"a/b/c"` → `["a", "a/b"]`); the full stroke itself is never included, so an entry cannot suppress its own terminality.

`pub fn fix_family_terminals(entries: &mut [TypedEntry])` builds a `HashSet` of all proper prefixes across every entry's stroke, then clears `terminal` on any entry whose stroke exactly matches one of those prefixes. Only flips `true` → `false`; never sets an entry terminal that wasn't already. Depends on `TypedEntry` from the parent `expand` module (specifically its `stroke: String` and `terminal: bool` fields) — if that struct's field names or stroke representation change, both `proper_prefixes` and the matching logic here need updating in lockstep.